There are times when I feel a deep sense of shame for being European.
In the past year, over a million people have arrived in Europe seeking help, and frankly, our response has been shameful.
It's just riddled with contradictions at this point.
We all mourned the tragic death of two-year-old Alan Kurdi, but since then, over 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean one after another.
Despite recognizing the need for shared responsibility in accepting refugees under international agreements, we tacitly accept the fact that the number of refugees taken in by the small country of Lebanon exceeds the total across all of Europe.
While we lament the existence of smuggling boats, we have made them the only route to asylum in Europe.
Despite a labor shortage, we are excluding people whose skills match our economic and demographic needs from being accepted.
While we claim to uphold liberalism against Islamic fundamentalism, we are doing so with repressive policies that detain young asylum seekers, separate children from their families, and confiscate refugees' belongings.
Don't you think that's strange?
Why have we become so inhumane in our response to this humanitarian crisis?
I don't think it's because people are indifferent. At least, I don't want to believe that's the reason.
I believe it's due to a lack of vision among politicians; a vision to adapt international refugee policies, established over 50 years ago, to the changing era of globalization.
I would like to return to the basics and pose two very fundamental questions that we all should consider.
First, why isn't the current system working?
And, how can we fix this?
The modern refugee system is something they created in the immediate aftermath of World War II.
The original purpose was to provide people with a destination when states collapse, or, in the worst case, turn their swords against their own citizens, and to offer them a place where they can live with safety and dignity until they can return home.
It was designed to address situations like what we see in Syria today.
It is an international agreement signed among the governments of 147 countries - through treaties such as the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and via international organizations like the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, they have pledged to mutually accept refugees into their own territories; it is about the acceptance of people fleeing from conflicts and persecution.
But today, this system is not functioning.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In reality, our immigration policies are blocking the path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek integration into their place of refuge, with the expectation that they may one day return home.
In reality, it ends up in a virtually permanent state of limbo.
In theory, refugees are meant to be shared in a spirit of global responsibility.
In reality, it is the countries adjacent to conflict zones, due to geographical proximity, that end up shouldering the overwhelming majority of the world's refugees.
The reason the system is not functioning is not because the rules are wrong,
It is because we are failing to properly apply the rules in accordance with a changing world, and it is this that we need to rethink.
Here, what exactly is the mechanism of the current refugee system?
Let me explain a little.
However, I will explain from the perspective of the refugees, not from the top-down viewpoint of the system.
First, please imagine a Syrian woman.
Let's call her Amira.
She is a woman who symbolizes many people from her region.
Amira, like a quarter of the world's refugees, is a woman with children. The reason she cannot return home is that the city she lived in is in the state you see – Amira's city, Homs, was once a beautiful and historic place, but now it is buried in rubble.
It is not a situation where they can return.
However, resettlement in a third country is not an option for Amira, as it is akin to winning the lottery, a possibility that materializes for only one percent of the world's refugees.
As a result, Amira and her family are forced into almost impossible choices.
There are only three basic options available.
The first is to enter a refugee camp with her family.
There, they may receive aid, but prospects for Amira and her family's future are virtually non-existent.
Refugee camps are barren wastelands - often in the middle of deserts.
In Jordan's Zaatari refugee camp, the sound of gunfire can be heard at night from the border with Syria.
There are constraints on economic activity.
The quality of education is also poor.
And around 80% of refugees worldwide who are housed in camps will endure such conditions for a minimum of five years.
Life there is miserable, and perhaps for that reason, only 9% of Syrians actually choose this route.
The second option is to head for urban centers, such as Amman or Beirut, in neighboring countries.
This is the option chosen by 75% of Syrian refugees.
But there too, they face significant challenges.
Refugees typically do not have the right to work in these urban areas.
They are also unable to receive much assistance.
In this case, after exhausting their savings, Amira and her family are left with virtually nothing, facing a life of poverty in the city.
The third option — the number of Syrians choosing this is increasing.
This is the phenomenon seen in Europe today, where, for the sake of their families, people are embarking on extremely perilous journeys in search of a glimmer of hope, risking their lives to head for foreign lands.
The world presents these virtually impossible choices to refugees, limiting their options to three: camp confinement, a life of poverty in the city, or embarking on a perilous journey.
For refugees, this is precisely what the international refugee system itself has become.
But thinking that this is the only option is an illusion.
I believe there is room for reconsideration.
The reason we confine them to these options is because, in our minds, we think the paths available to refugees are limited to these alone, but that is incorrect.
Politicians view the refugee issue as a "zero-sum" problem - that is, they believe that anything done for refugees comes at the expense of their own citizens.
We tend to share the assumption that refugees are a burden and a weight on society, as if it's a common truth.
There are also ways in which refugees can contribute to society.
What I am saying is that there are ways to expand the options for refugees while ensuring that everyone benefits - the host countries and communities, our societies, and the refugees themselves.
I believe that by considering four approaches I will discuss, we can fundamentally change our thinking about refugees.
One common thread among all four is the approach of utilizing opportunities created by globalization, mobility, and markets, which can transform our perspective on the refugee issue.
The first idea is about creating environments suitable for refugees, starting from a very basic understanding: that refugees are just like everyone else, simply placed in extraordinary circumstances.
I began research with a colleague from Oxford University in Uganda, looking into the economic activities of refugees.
I didn't choose Uganda because it is a leading recipient country in the world.
Because it has an excellent policy in place.
Unlike other recipient countries around the world, Uganda provided economic opportunities to refugees.
It granted refugees the right to work and the freedom of movement.
This has yielded remarkable results for both the refugees and the regions where they reside.
In the capital, Kampala, 21% of refugees own businesses and employ workers, with 40% of those employed being citizens of the host country.
In other words, refugees were creating jobs and employing citizens of the host country.
Even within refugee camps, we saw impressive examples of vibrant individual enterprises.
For instance, in the Nakivale refugee settlement, Congolese refugees are involved in a business trading digital music.
A venture started by a Rwandan refugee involved providing computer games, repurposed from gaming consoles and televisions, for teenagers.
