When I arrived at the settlement, I was virtually penniless but aspiring to be a video producer.
He, along with friends and colleagues, established a community radio station and, borrowing a video camera, is now engaged in video production.
He has co-produced two documentary films at the request of my team and is successfully running his business with a minimal initial investment.
We should let such examples guide our response to refugees.
Instead of inevitably seeing refugees as dependent on humanitarian aid, we need to provide them with opportunities to prosper as human beings.
Of course, clothing, bedding, shelter, and food are all crucial in an emergency, but we need to look beyond these immediate needs.
Opportunities such as access to communication, electricity, education, the right to work, and access to capital and banks.
We must ensure that benefiting from the world economy is something that is not only commonplace for us but also possible and rightful for refugees.
The second is an idea concerning economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all of the world's refugee-hosting countries have adopted a policy like Uganda's.
Most countries do not welcome refugees into their economies in the same manner as Uganda.
However, practical solutions that can be adopted do exist.
Last April, I traveled to Jordan with my colleague, the development economist Paul Collier. During our stay, we engaged in brainstorming sessions and held discussions with the international community and the Jordanian government, seeking ways that align with Jordan's national development strategy.
We came up with a way to provide jobs for Syrians, an idea involving economic zones where the employment of refugees could be integrated with that of the host country's citizens, the Jordanians.
Just 15 minutes away from the Zaatari refugee camp, home to 83,000 refugees, lies the King Hussein Bin Talal Development Area, an economic zone.
The Jordanian government has invested over a million dollars to connect this area to the power grid and road network, but two things are missing: labor and domestic investment.
What if refugees could work here? What if, instead of being confined to the camp, they could support their families and acquire skills through vocational training before returning to Syria?
We believed this would be beneficial for Jordan, because as a middle-income country, Jordan's development strategy required the expansion of its domestic manufacturing sector.
Not only would it be beneficial for the refugees, but it would also contribute to the post-conflict reconstruction of Syria, nurturing the best human resources to eventually rebuild Syria—a recognition that the protection and development of refugees is essential.
When we published this proposal in the political journal 'Foreign Affairs',
It caught the attention of King Abdullah.
At a Syria support conference held in London two weeks ago, it was announced that there would be a pilot implementation this summer.
The third idea I'd like to propose to you all is a matching system between countries and refugees, one that leads to delightful outcomes such as the one depicted in this photo, where a Syrian refugee is taking a selfie with Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Asking refugees about their hopes and where they want to go doesn't happen very often, does it? Yet, it is possible for everyone to benefit while listening to the voices of the refugees.
The concept of matching theory, developed by economist Alvin Roth, involves determining the final combinations based on the preferences of the parties involved.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Titelboim explored how to apply this concept to refugees, asking them to list their preferred destinations in order of choice, while simultaneously having host countries prioritize the type of refugees they prefer based on criteria such as job skills and language, then matching the two parties accordingly.
Now, of course, the criteria for acceptance should also take into account factors such as diversity and vulnerability, but these too can be considered ways to increase the matching rate.
The concept of matching is effectively utilized in various scenarios, such as university admissions for students and the pairing of kidney donors with patients, and it even plays a role in algorithms used on dating websites.
Why not incorporate this to expand the options for refugees?
It can also be applied at the national level. One of the major challenges we face is gaining the acceptance of refugee settlements from local communities.
Currently, for instance, in my country, the UK, we often do the ridiculous thing of sending engineers to the countryside and farmers to the city.
By conducting market matching, we can align the preferences of both parties, and listen to the needs and desires of both the residents of the host communities and the refugees.
And the fourth idea is humanitarian visas.
Almost all of the tragedies and chaos unfolding in Europe are entirely avoidable.
It is due to the fundamental contradiction in Europe's refugee regulations. What this means is that to become an asylum seeker in Europe, one must arrive having undertaken the aforementioned perilous journey without prior preparation. But why is such a journey necessary?
In an era with budget airlines and robust consular services, such journeys should be utterly unnecessary; yet, last year, over 3,000 people died undertaking them, at Europe's borders and within Europe itself.
Simply put, if refugees were allowed to travel to Europe regularly and become asylum seekers, these tragedies could be avoided. The way to make this happen is through something called humanitarian visas, which can be obtained from embassies and consulates in neighboring countries. Then, simply by paying their own fare, refugees could travel to Europe by ferry or plane.
Using smugglers to cross from Turkey to the Greek islands costs 1,000 euros.
A budget airline ticket from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs 200 euros.
There are significant advantages to unlocking such options for refugees.
Many lives would be spared, the refugee smuggling industry would dry up, and chaos would be removed from the front lines of Europe, such as the Greek islands.
What is obstructing such measures is not a lack of sensible strategies, but policy.
This idea is actually being implemented.
Brazil has pioneered this approach, admitting more than 2,000 Syrians who obtained humanitarian visas to enter the country and gained refugee status upon arrival.
All the Syrians who utilized this system have attained refugee status and have been officially recognized as refugees.
There are also historical precedents.
Between 1922 and 1942, the Nansen passport was used as an international identity document, enabling 450,000 Assyrians, Turks, and Chechens to move within Europe and apply for refugee status in other European countries.
The Nansen International Office for Refugees was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, recognizing the practicality and effectiveness of this strategy.
All four of the ideas I've discussed would increase the options for hypothetical refugee Amira, mentioned at the beginning.
This expands the range of options for refugees, meaning they aren't limited to the three unreasonable choices I initially mentioned, and it benefits everyone else as well.
In conclusion, we desperately need a new vision - one that recognizes that expanding refugees' options does not have to be a burden.
The notion that refugees inevitably become a burden is mistaken.
While they carry a humanitarian burden, refugees are people with skills, talents, and ambition, and if given the opportunity, they have the ability to contribute to society.
In the years to come, there will be no shortage of people migrating around the world.
What is happening in Europe will continue for many years to come.
Refugees will continue to move, wandering in search of a place to belong. To address this situation, we should seek rational and realistic methods - not those based on outdated theories of humanitarian assistance or notions of charity, but rather approaches that harness opportunities created by globalization, market dynamics, and mobility.
I want to appeal to all of you, and especially to the politicians among you, to wake up and confront this challenge directly.
Thank you.
